January 30 at 8:03 PM ·

Dear Classmates from the years 1974 and 1975. We are trying to gather current mailing addresses, email addresses and phone numbers of our classmates.
Please send me your addresses, if you have not already done so. If you happen to have other classmate contact information, we would appreciate your sending them, even if they are duplicates. We are planning our reunions and looking forward to reaching as many classmates as possible. Thank you! Nancy :)

February 13 at 4:52 PM ·

The West Geauga Marching Band is thrilled to receive an official invitation to the 2022 London New Year's Day Parade! Thank you to the Lnydp for coming to WGHS to present our invitation!

Video of the assembly can be found here - https://sites.google.com/westg.org/westgeaugabands/videos/london

We are excited for the opportunity to perform live for hundreds of thousands of people, and hundreds of millions on television!! Trip information will be available in the coming months for the 2021/22 WGMB, we will keep you posted!

post_text:
The “Kiwanis 100 Bags of Hope” is a food donation program that tries and helps meet the needs of local Geauga families with children which includes local Geauga County Veterans families. The program was inspired by Maureen Kilroy and the Andrew Spirit of Hope Foundation (ASH). The ASH Foundation is in memory of Andrew Horning, a WG student, and supports local food programs in memory of Andrew. After the Holiday donation season is over, many local families are faced with the decision to pay heating or buy groceries. When there is a “snow day” some children may not get lunch as the schools provide them lunch. 100 bags of Hope tries to help address that problem.

Each year West Geauga Kiwanis and local volunteers, like the Chester chief of Police, Trustees, Fire chief, boy scouts, the West Geauga Local Schools, and Girl Scouts get together to pack 100 bags of groceries for the needy. This is the 3rd year for the program which has donated over 3 1/2 tons of food to local families through Job and Family, local food pantries and local schools.

West G Hosts Newbury Families for Open House

West Geauga Local Schools hosted an Open house for students and families from Newbury Township at the High School on Wednesday, January 15, 2020. Many of these students will be attending West G for the 2020-2021 school year. The West Geauga Board of Education approved the territory transfer of Newbury Township into the district in December. At the event, over 40 organizations, teams, teachers and parent groups showcased the wide variety of activities that are available to students. The night was welcoming to these newest members of the West Geauga Community.

Pacifico wins WG District Spelling Bee!
Elementary and Middle School Students Competed at the annual District Spelling Bee on Tuesday, January 14, 2020 at Westwood Elementary School. Winners of the individual building bees spelled a wide variety of words following the Scripps National Spelling Bee format. Sixth grader Parker Pacifico won the bee and will move on to the Geauga County Spelling Bee representing the West Geauga Local School District on February 6, 2020 at the Geauga County Educational Service Center at 7:00 pm.

West G Hockey Team Revival
Sparked in large part by a record turnout at the 21st annual Turkey Bowl, alumni, parents and high school students galvanized on a plan to resurrect the West Geauga High School Varsity Hockey Team, which has been on hiatus for several years. Within the ever-growing West G school district, we have identified a core group of players who have a desire to play for their school. There is also an interest among current students who are not experienced at hockey but have expressed a willingness to learn this terrific sport.

Join us for a meeting on Tuesday, January 14th in the High School Library from 7-8 p.m. All interested players, parents, and volunteers are…

post_text: Laura Palmer, the secretary of Lindsey Elementary School, has decided to retire. Just over 25 years ago Mrs. Palmer began her career with the West Geauga Local Schools, and now she has decided to move on to activities with her family, friends, and grandchildren. The West G family will miss her greatly and we wish her well in her retirement. Congratulations, Mrs. Palmer!

post_text: Fourth grade student, Lena Wright submitted an essay to the Geauga County Auditor’s “Is Your Dog #1 in Geauga County?” contest back in October. The Chief Fiscal Officer, Charles E., Walder, Geauga Dog Warden, Mathew Granito, and Executive Director of Rescue Village, Hope Brustein, visited Mr. Croff’s Classroom on Monday, December 9, 2019 to award Lena the winner of the contest. Her dog, Jenny, received dog tag #1 and the title of #1 Dog in Geauga County. She also received other prizes from the presenters, and Mr. Croff was awarded $250 for his classroom. Great Job Lena!

post_text:
Students Fare Well in Chinese speech competition at the Confucius Institute at the University of Akron

Members of the Chinese class at West Geauga High School won 3rd place at the Chinese Speech Competition at the Confucius Institute at the University of Akron. Middle school Student, Quinn Misterka, won 3rd place in the middle school student Chinese essay competition and Bridget Bellett, Maddox Schaffer, Thomas Romeo, Andrew Elias, and Madelyn Scott earned honorable mention in the middle school student Chinese essay competition. The Confucius Institute Chinese Language and Culture Outreach program was attended by 260 students from six schools in the greater Cleveland and Akron areas. Our students performed well as they have only been studying Chinese for 2 ½ months at West Geauga Local Schools.

post_text:
Hillcrest Insurance West Geauga Student Athletes of the Month

Rylie Hanford
Rylie is a Sophomore on the Girls Tennis Team. Rylie was the Chagrin Valley Conference Singles Champion and League MVP this year. Rylie also placed 3rd in the State Tennis Tournament for the second consecutive year. She is on the Honor Roll and plans to play Division I Tennis majoring in Business and Engineering in College. Her parents are Kim and Ken Hanford.

Patrick Garrett
Patrick is a Junior on the Boys Cross Country Team. Patrick helped lead his team to a Runner-up finish in the CVC Championships and a qualifying birth in the Regional meet. Patrick was the runner-up in the CVC individually as well as an Individual State Qualifier. Patrick also plays basketball and runs track. He is undecided in his College plans. He is the son of Denise and Jim Garrett.

post_text:
West G Help Mr. Roman Celebrate his 100th Birthday

Students at Westwood Elementary and Lindsey Elementary Schools sent birthday cards and well wishes to Mr. Roman to celebrate his 100th birthday on November 14th. His son, Joe Roman, whose children are Graduates of West Geauga Local Schools, contacted the school district with a request to send his father cards for his monumental birthday. Teachers and students were happy to honor his request sending dozens of cards to Mr. Roman. Happy 100th Birthday, Tony Roman!

Geauga Achieve Celebrates Thanksgiving with Families

Students in Mrs. Kustron’s Classroom took on the enormous undertaking of hosting a Thanksgiving Meal for their families. Students created invitations, shopped for food, prepared the food, set the tables and served this feast to their families. Mrs. Kustron and Mrs. Larrick have made this a tradition at West Geauga Middle School for many years.

post_text: The West Geauga Middle School hosted the annual College and Career Readiness Day on November 21, 2019. 8th Grade students heard a keynote speech delivered by John Gadd, President and CEO at Hotcards.com, followed by numerous sessions with speakers from a wide variety of occupations. Students also heard presentations from specialized programs such as Excel TECC, as well as presentations from area universities. School Councilor, Dusty Timmons, planned and organized this event for our students.

post_text:
Dear West Geauga Parents/Guardians:

We will soon begin discussions related to the topic of grade level elementary buildings as a possible alternative to two K-5 buildings. The West Geauga Board of Education and administration are preparing to involve staff, parents, and residents in those discussions now that the initial feasibility issues related to space, transportation, etc. have been examined.

The Board has not made a decision about building reconfiguration at this point. It is however studying the possibility. Several educationally-compelling reasons support the decision to explore reconfiguration of the elementary schools. If reconfiguration occurs, it will most likely take the form of…
